\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 s, shops all in - Cardiff, they were - everything was bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When would you have new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 As a rule, on a Whitsun. Whitsun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about shoes, would you have new shoes or second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - all - never second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hand. We never had second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hand clothes nor shoes, if we didn't have 'em we go without them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where would she buy the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Cardiff in - ah now let me think now }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  Hayward}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 s and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  Oliver}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 s.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When would you have new shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - when you could afford 'em. But we did always try - to have all new things if we could for Whitsun Monday. That was a special day.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes, and - and matter of fact - we children when we got old enough to do a little bit, we always helped in the house as well. Father had - oh yes, my father helped in the house a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did he do, in which way would he help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well he'd help with washing the dishes and he'd - do a little bit of painting - or any little odd jobs that had to be done, he'd do 'em.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would he do any cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, he'd do the fires. Aye, he'd do the fires.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 And he'd do decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do decorating, oh he'd do a lot of decorating, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - he'd always do any little odd repair that was possible for a man to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, he'd do any improvements that want - was wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would he ever dress you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. I never remember my father dressing one of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Undress you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh sometimes, yes, tell us stories. Oh aye, he was very good at telling stories. Yes, he'd tell us stories hours at a time. Oh yes. Very big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hristian man he was and my mother. They were big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
hristians - used to take a great interest in the chapel, c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
ntatas, Band of Hopes and all that sort of stuff. And my sisters followed in their footsteps. My sister became a - well, professional sing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 er. She was Madam Bebe Griffith}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  the contralto singer. Competed ninety-two times and were never beaten. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your father ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would he look after you when she was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, oh yes, yes, aye, but in those 
days - they were never out apart from one another. They - when they ever went out the two went together. We children went with them. Because - it was very poor times in those days, and you didn't have the money to spare, there were no buses - trave}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6519037\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 ling fr
om Tongwynlais to Cardiff. If you wanted to go to Cardiff you either had to walk to Tapswell and catch a train or walk to Cardiff. You see there was not - there were - it isn't like it is today. You can step on a bus and go in, there were no buses. Oh yes
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yu did mention that you helped in the house. Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, I had to go up the wood every Saturday morning, and - bring sticks, carry sticks home - for the morning fires.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 That was your job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Always, aye, and you had to see that the sticks were there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How long did you continue to do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 'Til I was seventeen. Yes. 'Til I was seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh my brother was the same, he'd have to do it too. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 The same job or another job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, no, no, my brother would clean all the shoes. Weekends, and do - sweep up the back. That was his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your sisters, what about Amy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh well now Amy was - a schoolteacher - she became
 - a pupil teacher, and she did nothing else, only study - the piano, and - to be a teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about when she was a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh when she was a little girl - she done a lot of little odds and ends in the house. Helping my mother with this 
and the other. But no heavy work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about Elizabeth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Ah now - now she - she was a little tartar for sewing, from the - from - her early age of seven or eight year old, she always had a needle and cotton. And she became a tailoress in the wind
 up, but she was always doing any little bit of sewing, and she used to do darning, and my other sister Phoebe. Yes, they'd do a little bit of darning. When they were small, yes. And - oh yes, and I can tell you this much too - if we didn't have a new sui
t
 or a - suit to go out, we'd have to stop in on a Sunday. Oh aye, oh yes. And we didn't do like they do today. You would have a new suit and would put it on Monday and Tuesday, Wednesday. There was a suit always - for Sunday. And you couldn't wear that an
y other day, only on Sundays. See, until it was - be - get - when it - the time come when you'd have to have a new suit, then you could wear that one - in the evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What were Phoebe's jobs, she'd help with the darning would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Blod - Phoebe used to help with the darn - and - from a young age - she would help all the other children. Yes, from a young age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In what way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 If they - if - any of the youngest - the ones under her, she'd help to undress them and - wash them - and look afte
r them, and she was very good - at laying the tables and jobs like that you know. Everybody had their own job, everybody had to do something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would Blodwen's job be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Ah ha, ha, well now Blowen was a very delicate girl when she was young, so
 she never done much. No. She'd - more or less - was pampered by the rest of the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Because she was the baby too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 She was the baby, aye. And she was pampered by the rest of the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 So she didn't have to do much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. Never. N
ever. Never never, never. No. And she become - well she's going about preaching today. She's a preacher - preacher now in the chapels. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mentioned that the older children helped the younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you help them and Amy, or was it only Phoebe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, Amy and Phoebe helped them, oh yes. But I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did the younger children help the older ones at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well no, I mean - you see what you - don't realize that - that the movement we became twelve year old, we had to find a job 
and go to work, I went to work when I was twelve. I worked in Melingriffith tinworks when I was twelve years old. So there were no - and it - it wasn't working - six seven hours, twelve hours a day. Six in the morning 'til six in the night. Saturday six i
n
 the morning 'til two dinnertime. For nine and fourpence a week. Aye, oh aye. Very lot of hard work and times were very very - very bad in our place in those days. Until they built the Cardiff railway. And then - they brought into the - little village, hu
ndreds of - Irishmen and - navvies from all over the place, and they called it in - for a while - the notorious village. Oh aye. Well - we had - when they built that Cardiff railway there were seven pubs in that village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When was that? How old would you have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
About fifteen. About seventy - about sixty-six, sixty-seven years ago, they built that Cardiff railway, and the - it was a very quiet - little village in them days. But when they opened the Cardiff railway of course we had all the - riff
-raff and the Irishmen, and all - and navvies coming in, and we had seven pubs in the small village like it was you know. And there were - Saturday nights - it was nothing there Saturday nights and see the fights and things on the doors. And then I - went
 
to a chapel on a - on a Boxing Day to see a concert, Come out from the concert - and I was twelve year old, and - oh - thirteen probably, and I saw a man - killed on the road, another man come out of the pub, followed him out - and hit him agen a post and
 
killed him on the side of the road. Yes. Aye, there was a - two murders there. Lot of suicides in them days. Oh aye, aye, the Peartrees murder they called it, where an old man went a bit wild and - killed his wife and his - daughter. And suicides, oh ther
e
 were - no end there. It got a very very rough village in them days. Terrible. But then in due course we had - we were unusual you see for a small village and we were. We had a market like Cardiff market there. We had a tan-yard there. Castlecork we had. 
S
ee, then we used to have the Marquis of Bute and Prince of Wales. Duke - Duke of Windsor come there to stay. And I - my father had a little choir, and we used to go up - to the Castle, invited - to sign in the - for - to the Lord Ninian Steward. Going out
,
 give a concert up there. And we were well - at - in them days we were recognised as - the finest little concert party in the country. And then when the Duke of Windsor came there, he stayed there a bit and my fa - my uncle - was a carpenter for the Marqu
i
s of Bute, and he made all the wooden chaneliers, to put the candles in when the Duke of Windsor were there. And he stayed there - looking after the candles and lighting them while the - the visit of the Duke of Windsor. And my father's brother - was a ca
r
etaker at Castle Cork - for fifty years. Yes. Oh aye. Oh there were - wonderful - atmosphere in the village there was as well. After all the old trouble blew over when the - the railway was finished and we had the station - then we had a wonderful class o
f
 people there. Helped one another. And we used to perform cantatas and concerts - and there was no one wanted although we were so poor. But very hard work - tin workers, and only work we had here then was the tinworks, and the quarries. If they wanted to 
go to the colliery well they'd have to go up by train to the colliery see. Oh yes, there was - some very good times here and some very bad times.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When you were a little boy were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Oh Lord yes. S
even o'clock you had to go to bed whether you liked it or whether you didn't. Aye, and - and you couldn't stop in bed after seven in the morning either. You'd be up at seven too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, we had to undress and go to bed ourselves. They'd see that you were washed mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What age would that be you'd put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Six, seven year old. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you share the bedroom with anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh my brother and I had a - oh - that's all, my brother and I had a - the smallest bedroom. Well -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have the same bed, were you in the same bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Shared a bed with your brother, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember how the rest of the family slept?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, my - three - younges
t sisters, the small ones, they slept together, no - two or 'em, Amy and - Phoebe, and then - Blodwen - and when - the - Lilla by herself and when Blodwen come along - she slept with her. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 They were in one room were thery,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 One - one room.
 We had - three rooms and a box-room. And - my brother and I - had the box-room. The other two - two girls each had the other two rooms, and mother and father had the front room. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh we had a bath downstairs in front of the fire. There was no bathrooms then. Oh a big tub in front the fire. I don't bother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Twice a week. Yes. Wednesday night and Saturday night. Yes. And there were no question about whether you wanted a bath or whe
ther - whether - whether you didn't, you had to bath, whether you liked it or not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you all bath in front of one another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, ah when we were young - oh yes, yes, yes. And I had an aunt - that lived close by us. And she used to - stutter. A
nd she worked in the tin works. But when we were very young - she'd come across to bath us all to help my mother. And as she was bathing us, smack across your backside as you got out as well you know. Aye. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When you got older how did you manage, the boys and the girls? Would people walk in and out while you were bathing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh no, no. No, no, no, no, no, no, no. Oh no, that's - you see, this - is where I lose everybody today. We did - used to be a little bit discreet about things like that. S
ee you - no tom, Dick and Harry would walk in the house while you were bathing. Well your parents wouldn't allow 'm to you see if you were in - bathing. And anybody come in say, oh go round the front door. See they wouldn't - let you come - oh no, no, no.
 And-
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 People wouldn't walk in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh no. No, no, no, no. No, when I come back from the war - I went to the Army, I went to the Army, when I come back from war and got married - I went and lived at Tonrefail, and I was twenty-five now, and
 it shook me to death - to see the colliers - bathing in front of anyone, any woman next door walking in when he were bathing, didn't take any notice of 'em. Yes. Well - well - ah, not down here - at all, no, and when I went to Tonyrefial to live first - 
i
t shook me to death, when I - I got married of course and went there, my wife was - six years younger than me. And her father was a foreman in the colliery and her brothers worked - they'd all work - bath there and the people next door'd come in while you
 were bathing, didn't take any - no notice of 'em at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you have to bath like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, I wouldn't, no. No damned fear, no. But they used to see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would it be after the bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
After a bath - yes. Bath but you never had clean clothes - wouldn't have clean clothes Wednesday. Clean clothes Saturday. Saturday night you'd bath and have all clean clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 On the living room, in the kitchen we called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh, there would be - on a Sunday probably a - they used to take the preacher and that you see. And on the Sunday, if the preacher came to tea or to dinne
r - it would be in the middle room. That's where we'd have our dinner - our - tea and dinner that day. But other days, in the kitchen. And our kitchen was as big as this room to be honest with you. Very big kitchen. And then - my mother used to be - a mas
t
erpiece at making - faggots and black puddings and all. And she'd - set a day a week - to do this. And she'd - buy the lights and the liver from - the slaughterhouse, and she'd make a couple of hundred faggots, and the people used to come up from the vill
age with their basins to get 'em off her. Buy 'em of course. Oh yes, when my father had his fingers off that's how we lived. Yes, and there were no -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where would your mother cook then, what was the cooking equipment?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, she had a big stove. Had a big stove then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 A gas stove, yes. Big gas stove then. And I used to - we used to have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where did she cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In the kitchenette. Kitchenette, oh aye. I used to - the night before we make the faggots - her and I - we'd have this
 here, what do you call it, mincer, we'd mince all the onions, all the liver and all the bread, more - get it all ready, and she'd make the faggots on the following day, put 'em in their trays. And then the people 'll be coming up to buy 'em. Penny each. 
A
nd they were faggots in them days. Oh aye. Oh there was - lots of work - I used to go up to the Valley once every week, selling blackberries when the blackberry season was coming. And - that's how we had to live you see because - there were no - well if i
t
 - when you're talking about - Parish Relief, half a crown you'd get and no more. But nobody had Parish Relief, half a crown you'd get and no more. But nobody had Parish - nobody'd be bothered to get it because you could - you had to try to get - buy and 
s
ell and do something to make a bit of - if you couldn't you had to go in debt in your grocers shop, and pay it when you started to work. That's how we had to live in them days. And there were no cinema down I mean - when I started to work first - my - we 
were paid every fortnight. And my wages - was nine and four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15092507\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence a week. I'd get sixpence pocket money on the payday. And three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15092507\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence pocket money on the blank. That's how much money we used to have to spend for the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What do you mean on the blank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well when - you'd get paid once a fortnight. So get paid today, and then - on the blank, no, we get three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence. And perhaps you wouldn't have never believe this, but when I was a young man of seventeen or eighteen - we used to like to go to the Em
pire, and - we'd go to the Empire, and back - on a shilling. We'd - come - walk to Witchett and have a three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
penny ride on the horse bus. Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence, four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence to go in the balcony in the Empire. Penny for a packet of Woodbine across the street. Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 ha
'pence for fish and chips in Frederick Street. And walk - walk back home and have a penny left for - coll - collection on the Sunday. Out of a shilling. Oh Lord, aye, and - and Colonel Lewis, we had a - a - the Squire of the village you know - they - you 
h
ear people saying, oh - the old days are gone, but they were grand days when we had the Squire. He was a Colonel Lewis. He were a good man, if there were anybody - that he knew didn't have a bit of meat from Sunday, there'd be a rabbit there or a little b
i
t of meat from - we had to curtsey and - salute him when we see him on the road. But he was a hard worker mind. Hard worker. And - yes, when - once a week he'd come to the school, he'd say he want eight boys - to go beating - for them to shoot and that yo
u know, and we'd get one and six for the day and a rabbit. Oh God, we thought we were in heaven. One and sixpence. Oh we had some - we had some wonderful times. But it was very poor mind. Awfully poor.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, about q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 ua}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 rter past eight in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What members of the family were present then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
All of us, bar me father. 'Cos we all - we had to walk - a mile and a half to school every morning. We never went to school in Tongwynlais because we were in the wrong par
ish. Tongwynlais were divided into two parishes. Inglisinon, and the Whitchurch. Well we had to go the Anglosinon, Tapswell school. So we had to have our breakfast quarter past eight and walk to Tapswell school by nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your father, how would he manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well he - oh well he'd have gone to - he wouldn't - my - mother wouldn't get up with him. No, no, he'd be up about half past five, have his breakfast and go to work. And then he wouldn't come home again - again 'til about half past six or seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would he have for breakfast, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh always a bit of bacon. Aye, fa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  bacon at that. Always. And bacon in them days was about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence ha'penny a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did he have to drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh tea always, tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would you have for breakfast, the rest of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Sometimes cereals. Sometimes toast. Sometimes toast cheese. But very seldom ba - bacon, we couldn't afford it. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have anything different on certain days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 For breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes, yes, aye, now - perhaps - one day - we'd have eggs. 'Cos eggs then was thirteen - a - a - a dozen, thirteen for a shilling. And we'd have a egg perhaps today, and perhaps we'd have - a sausage or something - the next d
ay, then'd be a bit of toast, a bit of toast cheese, that's the sort of thing we used to live on. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about midday meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well, the mid - in the winter - it - it was stew and soup. See, but when we started to work - well we had to catch -
 what we could when we were children. We could never depend upon saying well we're going to have - a piece of lamb or this, you couldn't do it. Because you didn't know what you could get, you could. didn't know what you could afford. You could have a bit 
of fish. 'Cos fish was pretty cheap in them days. And you could have a bit of fish, and - in the night time - bit of bread and butter and jam. Oh yes. I never -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You wouldn't have an evening meal, like a dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no, no, midday day you'd have y
our dinner. The little bit of dinner that were left - would be your father's for the night. When he'd come home, 'cos he wouldn't have a midday meal. But - oh you couldn't depend on having - know what you were going to have. And when you go to bed in the 
night - you'd have a piece of bread and butter and jam, and a drop of milk probably and off to bed. There were no meal then. Oh no, you could - you couldn't do it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you have different on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 On a - on the Sunday - we always used 
to have - my mother would make a couple of plates of tart. And a jelly and a - custard. And that would be our tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about dinner on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well dinner - no - all we'd have a piece of meat and two - two veg - always. And - sometimes on a Sat
urday night - my father would be in Cardiff with my mother, and they'd - on the open air market they'd be selling - auctioning fish and that. You'd - you would probably buy - a nice bit of haddock and a couple of kippers and a couple of bloaters or - all 
f
or about sixpence see. Well then now - Saturday night, that'd be a special treat. Bit of fish before you go to bed. Oh you - you you had to live - from day to day on what you could get. You could never depend, and be - because - you had to work so hard yo
u see. We weren't in a position after we come from work, we weren't in a position to go out - and play about. Three nights out of every five you'd have to stop in 'cos you were too damned tired to go out. Too tired to go out you see. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
My mother did very often. My mother baked her bread very often. And we had an old oven outside and we had to bake the bread - with sticks. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Outside the house was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Outside, yes. And it was a lovely bit of bread too, and we used to keep pigs as well. Oh yes. Oh there were a lot of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, blackberry jam. Aye, oh Lord alive. And wine, elderberry wine. Oh Lord aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about bottled fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, never m
ake bottled fruit. Oh yes. I'm telling you a lie. We had a lot of blackcurrant trees in the garden, and she used to make a lot of - blackcurrant fruit you know. Oh she'd do that, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would she make pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. Never bothered about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You said she made wine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh made wine - very often, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Elderberry was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, aye, and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hubarb too. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would she make any medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was any beer brewed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no, no. No. No indeed. But - I didn't have - we didn't drink it mind but if one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 A lot used to have this diodfaen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes. Aye, I - of course we used to have a lot of grapes. Oh small beer. Oh we used to make a lot of that. Oh - oh with dandelions and - oh - aye, small beer we
 used to make no end of that, always had plenty of that in the house. Lord alive, aye. But - of course we had the - vineyards - opposite us. And there was all the grapes then you see. Used to go over there and pinch the grapes and - make wine, they belong
ed the Marquis of Bute, the Castle - the Castle Cork you know. Oh yes, there was a - and mind, plenty of fun in the village you see. Oh Lord alive.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mentioned you grew blackcurrants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes. Yes. Oh yes, always had our own garden and did - a - a part from our - kitchen garden, we'd have an allotment you see. Mm, aye.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 That helped didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh Lord, of course yes, and - we all used to make sure - that - it w
ould be finished Whitsun Monday. Before the Whitsun Monday treat - we'd make sure that - we'd work - do our garden - and we'd go over in the morning before the Whitsun Monday treat, to make sure that it were all finished. And then once a year - all the vi
l
lage - on Whitsun Monday would all Sunday schools would march around, and on the Tuesday - our - our general outing, Penarth for one day. We'd all go to Penarth for one day. Oh yes. We used to have - wonderful times and - but as for work mind - it was wor
k - work, work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
A chap living there, Dai Davis, he - he used to go in Tapswell to have a shave always. Afraid of this barber so he said to me - how is this - how is the lady barber Howell? Oh, I said, she's all right Harry. Good I said. You go to her.
 Can't go up, he said, it's snowing. Go on up, I said, be - go and have a shave with her, she's lovely man I said, only don't talk when she's shaving you. All right, he said. So we went in the barber's shop and he said, shave please Miss Canton. So she we
n
t to give him a shave and he's - like that, and I were listening now, I was sitting in the back behind him, and he was looking at me and and she said - and she was shaving him by here then, is the razor all right Mr Davis? And he was afraid to talk, he no
dded his head, he very nearly had his throat cut up. The best - best - war broke out on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 1914?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Aye, and my - three pals and myself - got a big tight, decided to go and join up with Colonel Lewis. So up we went to Colonel Lewis, and - and
 - twelve o'clock in the night. Knocked at the door, the butler come to the door - and the Colonel come, come in boys he said, I'm pleased to see you, I can see that you are joining, what is it, your King and country. In we went. Now what are you going to
 join he said to us. So I sai}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 d, well I'll join the Welsh regi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
ment sir. Now what about you - Davis? Well I'll join the Welsh regiment too sir. And we had one man, Phil}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Collins see, and he had fallen down on the way up to it and cut his head. So the Colonel said to him, what about you Collins, what will you join Scotch Highlanders sir - Colonel, he said}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 
. Oh, he said, join a regiment C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 ollins he said, Scotch Highlanders, join a Welsh regiment, he said, I've been in it fifty years. Aye, he said, but you've never 
killed a bloody man all the time you've been in it. Oh and - but - the biggest story was, there were a young man in the village, and - he always thought he was a great - fighting man. So he wanted to join - the Grenadier Guards. So we bluffed him up that 
h
e had to have a test for all this you see. He went up to be measured, and the Colonel Lewis said to him - the old Colonel was good for a joke, oh all right Edwards, he said - Grenadier Guards, well I don't know if you've got the courage for that, he said.
 
Oh yes, sire, he said, I've got the corage for it. Well all right, he said, we'll try you. Get the rifle out Cap - Harry, he said to Captain Harry. So Captain Harry got the rifle. Go over there Edwards, he said, and hold your coat well open like this. So 
C
aptain Harry - bang. Bullet hole through this side of the coat, bullet hole through that side of the coat. Put your hat up Edwards. Bullet through his hat. Well done Edwards, he said. I didn't think, he said, you had so much courage. Sharp, he said to the
 butler, get this boy a new coat and a new hat. And - Edwards said to him, and a new trousers sir. Yes. We didn't shoot your trousers. No sir, I know that. And we had a bloke there with a - one arm on -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 So your father and mother used to grow their own vegetables and fruit, did they buy any at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes. Oh yes, you had to buy - oh you couldn't buy - you couldn't - you see they wouldn't - we were too big a family, we - were eight with my mother and father, to make 'em last all year round.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would they have any tinned vegetables.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Dried vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Tinned fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No - oh yes, tinned fruit occasionally. That was on special occasions of course But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Dried fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Very seldom. What - like Chr
istmas dried fruit, raisins, currants for Christmas cakes and that. They used to make - a big do of all - special occasions. Good Friday, Easter Monday, Christmas, all that - was - a special do, always. And we were - used to live in the winter - mostly on
 pea soup. And that was a favourite of our family, my mother could make it. And she - when I come to think of it - the strength of the things that was in all this sort of thing. Nothing to go down and get six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pennorth of bones }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
 three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pennorth of bones, two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pennorth of bones, to make that sort of stuff. But you had to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  live on it see, there were no }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
other way of living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mentioned earlier that you kept pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye, we kept pigs. We kept a sow, and - we used to breed little pigs. And when they co
me to porkers about - four or five months old, they'd be about score or five, we'd kill 'em then, and sell 'em around the village. Have a butcher to cut 'em all up for us, and we'd sell it and I think very often about it now, belly pork'd be about eight}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pe
nce a pound. Or fillet would be about one and two, and today is a - is a million - you've got to be a millionaire to buy it. Oh yes, they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who looked after the pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - all of us, my father used to have a little - boiler up by the pig st
y, boil the - all the peelings and that ready for 'em. I had to take my turn to go and clean 'em out and help to feed 'em. Oh we all - and my mother too. We all done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, no, no, they never done it. They would - not a
nything like that because - although they - we were poor - in a way, we had a little bit of respect for the girls, we wanted them to try to be - a little bit different - to what - other girls were. They had singing lessons, they had music lessons, my sist
er died not many years ago, she had forty-five pupils in St David}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
s Hall in Whitchurch here, Madam Amy Jones. Well the other sister died - about a twelve month ago, the singer I told you. The other one was a tailoress and a good tailoress. But this youngest
 one now, she's the only girl alive now, she goes around - she's a president of all the sisterhoods - of - ware, and she goes around preaching you know, so we tried to - that was one of the things my mother always had in her mind, to try to give the girls
 - she didn't mind so much about the boys, how we got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you feel about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
No, didn't mind at all. Helped, we used to help. Yes, didn't mind. Damn, I used to work - I was working - slaving very often - I've sat in the house on a Sunday
 look - the preacher been there to tea - dinner and tea, and I've had to stop upstairs and never had a suit to go out, and my sister'd be all togged up to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 And you wouldn't be able to come downstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. Couldn't come down, you - 'cos - have to make some excuse why you weren't in chapel see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 So the preacher wouldn't know you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no, no, no. Yes, oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Nothing, you never used to care a damn. No, it was just one - one of those things a
nd - but - you see we used to - always - try to see the girls - a little bit - beyond than other people. Aye and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you keep hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye, and ducks. Aye, yes. Aye, we had - we had - brook below our garden, and we used to keep ducks, and we had 
twelve ducks. And I never remember anything like it. You could go down for about three months every morning like the clock and pick twelve eggs up. Never missed a lay, and then all of a sudden, you'd pick four up, then you'd pick two up, then you'd pick o
ne up. That finished. No more. They'd lay for so long, and that was it, and oh damn didn't we used to enjoy them, the duck eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would look after the ducks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, well we would, any one of us, oh they were no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about the hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 O
h the hens, well we had a nice - nice lot of hens, and - I tell you something which you will never believe now. I bought a cockerel from the vicar of Pendylon. A Rhode Island Red. A beautiful bird, and I bought the hen with it And - we had had 'em about t
h
ree months, and I went home one night and my mother said to me, that - hen that you bought last is bad. I went down to have a look at it, and it was. And I was about seventeen, perhaps a bit more. And I operated on it. And you are not going to believe thi
s
 but it's the God's truth I brought it up the house. I had a bit of board about that long, I put it on his back, tied his leg and a bit of cord around his neck. And a couple of nails in. I took a feather off his throat, cut it open with a razor blade, and
 
I cleaned the crop all out, and inside the crop - there was a blue stone. Poison to pick up. Cleaned it all out. Stitched it back up with a needle and cotton. Before I stitched it back up - put some - castor oil and milk - in his throat, stitched it back 
up, put it in a box by the side of the fire by here. Next morning when we come downstairs there was egg in the box. Yes, that's the God's truth. Nobody'd believe - but it's the God's honest truth. You'd never believe that would you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh damn, sometimes once. Very seldom more than once. Very seldom, without a Sunday of course, a Sunday was a special day and about once in the middle of the week. And it - and you wouldn't call it meat then, it - it was more or 
less bones you know. It was the cheapest you could buy, because my father's money I think - was about twenty-four shillings a week. And that's a lot - that's not much money is it. To keep eight on, no. But when you come to think of it - on the other hand 
you look at it this way you see. Sugar - was about a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hapence a pound. Butter - for sixpence or seven}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence a pound. You could buy cheese for tuppence ha'penny and three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence a pound. So you could buy a stack - for nothing. I have seen -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh no. no. Only - the only meat we'd have was corned beef. Had that, corned beef, but no other tinned. Well I don't remember any other, corned beef or - any other meat about in those days. No, I - I don't - no, I don't remember - corned beef.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you ever have extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes, aye, and we go out poaching, get - a couple of rabbit very often. Aye, and I remember going out poaching one day and having two rabbits, and - Colonel Lewis had 
his hounds up above where we were living, put them - put the rabbits in the shed outside ready,, damned the hounds came there that night and pinched them. I then had to go out poaching again, we used to have a net and put 'em over the hole. Oh yes, and mu
s
hrooms. Go in the field and pinch the blessed mushrooms in - morning, three o'clock in the morning. Yes, get up early in the morning, and go up, pick about six, seven pound of mushrooms. And that used to help us to live, don't bother yourself. Oh gosh, ay
e. Aye, rabbit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You would do the poaching?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh Lord aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How often would you do it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Once or twice a week. Yes, aye. Go in the hedge, I'd go right up to Colonel Lewis's big house, the hedge by the side of hi
s - by the side of his house. Go in there and put nets down and - have a couple of rabbits. And sell one or two mind. Sixpence each, yes. You got wonderful -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you ever get caught?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, oh I was caught many times but - ah - and when you're goin
g out to pick blackberries, the farmer used to - around his - barns and that, he'd have an hedge you know, with tons of blackberries on. But you're not allowed on there. So I used to be in the fields close by and waiting now - for him to bring - take his 
c
attle in, to milk 'em. And as soon as he'd go in there I'd be in this field. Have, oh - seven or eight pound of blackberries while he was milking the cows. Many times you - he come out and caught us you know but I was faster than him. I could go and he'd 
b
e after me but - he never caught me. I remember taking a job once, oh - times were bad, we were out of work anyhow, taking a job on of - picking stones - in a field you know. Penny a bucket. And the field was - oh, about a - mile square. And you had to ca
r
ry the stone when you fill a bucket up you carry and tip 'em down here. You'd be about half an hour up and down you know. So - I said to this chap - I had filled eight buckets, and I'd been hour, well Spencer Thomas I said to him - how about giving me six
pence out of my eight}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence Mr Thomas? Oh no, he said, you won't be paid 'til you've finished the field. Oh, I said, well that's no good. Oh no, he said, well have to finish the field - at the end of the month, when you get paid. Well, he said, oh all right
 then. So I'll come up tomorrow. Right. And on the way down the path - this chicken coup, I went in there, went through the chicken house, I had the six eggs. So I never went back no more, I had the eggs, instead of my pay. Oh it was - but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes, I do. Yes. Yes. I'll tell you something. We used to pick blackberries - Monday - all day, and my mother take 'em up to Ferndale on the Tuesday. And - she'd bring a pi
le of food back, with the money, and Wednesday and Thursday be all right, now she's going up again Friday. And I've seen us without food in the house - Friday morning, waiting for her to go up to Ferndale to sell the stuff to bring a bit of food back. And
 we couldn't afford for two of us to go up to Ferndale}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  to sel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
l 'em. I used to walk a mile and a half to Taps well station - to meet my mother coming off the train, to help to carry the groceries home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you think about it then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - I m
ean it were just a day's work, it were just - one of the things that we were used to, one of the things that we couldn't bother much about. I mean if people had to do it today you'd - well if they didn't have a fiver in their pocket a day they'd begin to 
gripe. But I mean it was one of the things, and it was out of work remember. You couldn't go from here to there and get a job. Oh no, you'd have to search and - you'd a devil of a job to get a job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your father have more food do you think than the rest of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
No, I wouldn't say he did. I wouldn't say he did. My father was a terrible man for cheese. And he'd be - if - if he - if we'd let him, he would live on bread and cheese. And I think mind it done him good too, 'cos he lived 'til he 
was eighty-five. Yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes. Yes. No, there was no - only when the preacher was there. Couldn't talk when the preacher was in, we used to hate to see the bugger coming. But - oh I mean we never used to take like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye, whatever was there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no, no, no, no, no. And if you said, I don't want this mum, I can't eat i
t, well - she'd say, well - I don't what else can have my boy, there's - this is all we've got. If could choose anything else you're welcome to have it, it didn't mat - didn't matter see. But there was a - there were no - hard and fast rule about - you've
 got to have this, you've got to eat that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What was your parents attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 They never both}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 red much, they said, you know, well look - don't waste it or don't have - but if you didn't want it you couldn't
 eat it and that was that, they never - my people - wasn't a family to shove down whether you wanted it or whether you didn't. We were trying not to waste it naturally. We never did waste, but matter of fact we didn't ever have - too much on the plates.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Very seldom. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye. Aye. That was one of the things they were particular about, not any certain way but - you had to use 
your knife and fork. And if you left your spoon standing up in a cup that'd be - you'd have it for that too. Oh no, they were very particular about things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have to sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Aye, bring toys, aye. Yes. In our - in our - it - it wasn't like that in our house. It wasn't - it wasn't like that, but - you see, my mother - on a Sunday morning there'd be no excuse that you couldn't go to chapel if yo
u had your clothes. You had to go. And you had to go to Sunday school, and you had to go to chapel in the night. I remember Tong Fair Monday, was a very young boy, I was only twelve year old, and I can remember that as if it - this as if it was yesterday.
 We - the Tong Fair, Monday - was a big day - bit time in our village. The - all the village would be full of stalls all over the place. John Studd's fairs, and they had big meetings. And I remember a - a - I can - I can't speak Welsh but - Y}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 es Segad we us
ed to call him. He lived the - street with my father and mother. And my father made me go. And Tong Fairing. And I was sitting - here's a bal - balcony here, I'm sitting in the first seat of the balcony crying my eyes out. And the preacher is preaching, a
n
d a damaned good preacher mind, and I can hear old Yres Segad saying to my father - he's preaching he's touching the boy John. If he only knew it - was going in the fair I wanted to go. Aye, the preacher is touching the boy John, he said. Oh aye. And we h
a
d an old blacksmith then, and - he'd say you know - Tong Fair Monday is coming now - come in here now every day. And I'd go in dinnertime, blowing the bellows - for him to make horses shoes. In the night as soon as I come home from school, blowing. I'm do
i
ng this for about three months - to get my pay now for - Tong Fair Monday. Tong Fair Monday down there now - to get - blow again, about half past eleven he'd say, there you are my boy. Go home now and - wash and change and - come down and fetch your pay. 
And I can see myself now. We'd have about three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence off my mother to go to the fair likely. And of course a roundabout's only a penny in them days. So I said to my mother, I can see my mother now - I don't know son, it's hard to find the money today. Well
 I don't want any pocket money mam, I said. I'm going to have my wages off - Frank the blacksmith. Oh well, she said, that'll be a help anyhow. And of course now I was expecting - to have a tidy bit of - so I go down ready now to go to the fair, walk in, 
h
ello Mr Thomas. Oh that's very good boy. Ah now you look - smart, but, of course you had bugger all on, only your corduroy trousers So he said - now let me see. Open a little leather purse he had. Searching. Now there you are, he said, be careful how you'
re spending it. A little three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 penny bit. Little three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 penny bit. To - after working all them days you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 He didn't give you any more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, a three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 penny bit. And I had given my mother - my three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence back to give to the children. But then we
 had to go down the fair, and pinch rides on the roundabouts and that, didn't - didn't used to worry much. Oh yes. But in - in - in a way - oh I - there was happiness then. With all there were hard times and all at once, it was happy times. Ah. When you w
a
nted to go - on a - any where - to play, nobody'd say anything to you if you go in the fields and have a game. And we never had a ball. We would have old - sugar bags - tie 'em up into a big - lump you know, for a football team. Couldn't buy a ball. And C
h
ristmas - I can see my Christmas stocking now. When I was ten, eleven year old. Used to go to bed, my father would hang your stockings up, and then we'd have in 'em - one new penny. Two oranges. Two apples. A sugar mouse, a sugar pig, and a sixpenny mouth
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 organ from Woolworth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 s. That was - cor we'd play all day then. We were happy as larks you know and delighted we'd be - blowing the mouth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8338586\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 organ all over the village. Oh they were good times. Ah.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When you were having a meal when could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh there were no - all you had to say to my mother was - all right mam if I go? Well, yes, go on. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you all sit at the table together for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 All - yes, all of us. All of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have the same places always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Always went in the same places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you sit round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well, as a rule - my father and my mother - my father would sit that end, my mother would sat that end, the three girls over there and the two boys and the girl, youngest girl - this side. That's how we - and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 So the baby would be next to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In - in - no, in between my brother and I as a rule, aye. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How would they feed themselves before they could feed, who would feed them when they were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh my mother, my mother would feed them, aye, but my mother wouldn't - went be - when they couldn't feed themselves, she'd have 'em by her. By her see, oh aye. When they - between us two, aye, and we'd help her if there anything you wanted to do, if she 
had a bit of meat, which she didn't have very af - often we'd given it her to - we'd cut it for her like. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye. Beautiful, anybody could talk to her. She was - one of the most liked women in the 
world. She - anybody, she'd do a good turn to anybody, and anybody could come and talk to her. But - nobody could catch her. She was as - smart by her as anything in the world. Couldn't come there and say to her, Mrs. Listen Maggie, I've got and so and so
 - cost two shillings. She didn't want to know. Oh no. But as good as gold she was, and my father mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did she show you affection?
