\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Aye, every - one outing a year. And that outing was to Pennarth. And every Whitsun Tuesday, the Whitsun - the Whitsun treat - would be on the Whitsun Monday. And Whitsun Tuesday - the whole of the village - would go by train to Pennarth for the day.
 That would be the yearly outing. And that's the only outing. Sometimes I had an uncle - and he was courting a girl in the village - I remember on one or two occasions - he - we got taken to the Empire in Cardiff. And she couldn't go. And I remember him t
a
king me and I can remember like yesterday - Houdini - were in the Empire. And I daresay I was about - twelve. And we went to Cardiff and up in the gallery. And there was a - a little play with a villain in it do you see. And I'd never been in the Empire i
n
 my life before, didn't know nothing about it. And this villain was coming out - and - the hero be coming behind him, and the villain, I - when he heard the hero coming - he went to hide behind the curtains, and I was so excited and lost my head - I shout
ed from the gallery - he's behind the curtains. Everybody in the Empire, hundreds of people - looked at us. Aye, as a - oh mind it was a big treat to go there go to the Empire. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Not in those - no, not then
, never went for holidays until - matter of fact 'til -about twenty-two or twenty-three years of age. That was the first time, and then - I went with my sister and her young man, and - another young couple, to stay in Weston.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When - that - that - wen
t - went to Weston, in about 1912. And that was really about the - first holiday I'd ever had. And - abut 1913 - I had an accident in the tin works. Cut my foot open. And I were home for practically a twelve month. Lost the use of my big toe. And a public
a
n - used to have a little pony and trap, and when I was - on crutches, he used to take me out along with him on his rounds. He was a traveller for Nells. Up Singaned, all over the country you know. And of course that - taught me to take a little drop see.
 
And - every day then it would be - a little drink here and little drink there, a and - my foot was poisoned, so I began back to work the end of 1913, And then on the Sunday night, the w a r broke out, the 1914 war. And then when I - that's when I joined t
h
e Army. I joined the Army then, and - joined that time for three or four years, and I gotmarriedin1916. My nurse - my wife was a nurse in the hospital down here. And I come back to that hospital, but we saw some very hard times before any of this you see.
 
There's a lot of people talk about - the - bad old days. But they weren't bad old days, they were hard days. Hard days. I do - anybody in my opinion that could live then - could always live, But we - we didn't have - we didn't seem to have the help - that
 they get now you see. But it - it were only bad if there were nobody in the house earning nothing. Parish Relief were that , half a crown a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you feel about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well we never had the parish relief because - my father had his finge
rs off, tops of fingers off, he was home for about - oh eighteen months, but as I told you - we'd do anything to earn a couple of shillings. I went picking stones in the fields, for days. And picking blackberry and mushrooms, elderberries, anything, I rem
e
m - I remember going to work - with an old man - selling Caerphilly cheese. And we used to go down to Cardiff and buy' this - Caerphilly cheese, we used to call 'em skimdicks. Tu-pence ha'penny a pound. And the cheese would weight perhaps - seven or eight
 
pound. And we had a clean sugar sack on the bottom of this cart, and we'd buy fifty or sixty cheeses. Lay 'em all out on this cart. And this old man was a crippled. They called him George Valor. And we'd be driving the horse anyway, come on Wes, we'll be 
a
 bit late today, And every pub he'd call on, he w a s deacon in the chapel, but every pub he called at to sell a cheese he'd say - give me half a pint. And - bring me half a pint out and - and he'd - drink it up, the landlord'd come out to have a look at 
the chees}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 , and I had a taster, and we had one special cheese to give 'em a bit to taste }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017 you see. And - there's one blue}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  rind cheese, and that was a lovely one. But they wouldn'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017 t}{
