Aye, well Saturday morning - Saturday morning - would be a big morning. First thing we do Saturday morning was come out - sweep the black - back, cut sticks, ready - for the morning, go up to the wood
 there and cut the bundle of sticks, you didn't have to cut them. The dead sticks were laying down in the wood. Take a big bundle of sticks, tie 'em up and b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 ing 'em home - for the morning. Then I always had two customers - tuppence a bundle - go up and cut more sticks. Take 'em to my two customers and that was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence pocket money - for the Saturday. Then after that, have our bit of dinner. Down the football field. Either playing a bit of football - with old balls or - anything'll do, or dawn the cricke
t field. A bit of mischief we were up to after, there were nowhere else to go, oh don't make any mistake, there were no - cars nor nothing on the road you know in those days. See, we made all our little bit of fun - ourselves, we had no recreation of any 
sort. And there was no recreation in the school mind you. Whatever you done, you done it yourself. And we used to play}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5572000\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
marbles. Play jack stones. And all this sort of stuff. But always down in a field in the summer in the river. Always in the river or the canal as soon as you had nothing to do, down the canal swimming. That's how we spent all our - time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh Sunday was a special day. With all our troubles, all our - poverty, you couldn't do anything on a Sunday. You shouldn't eve
n clean your boots on a Sunday in our house. No. Whether you like it or whether you didn't you go to chapel in the morning, by half past ten. Crying halfway down because you didn't really want to go. You'd come home, very often they'd have the preacher wi
t
h you if you had clothes to go, you'd have to go with - with them and come back. And then after dinner Sunday school. Out from Sunday school, and in those days - they used to come from Cardiff - horse and traps and - breaks, come out to the three mile lim
i
t - to have a drink on a Sunday. And there'd be horses to mind you know. We'd run dawn Woody chapel now about half past five. Six o'clock we'd go in. And we'd get a - somebody coming, we'd get a horse to mind. And we'd be watching our father going down - 
p
ast the chapel, and hiding behind the horse 'til he had gone in. But if you wasn't in there, he'd be out to look for you. So what we used to do, get some other little boy that didn't go to chapel, ask him to mind your horse 'til you come back, and give hi
m a penny out of what you'd get, and then you'd go to chapel. And we were waiting for him to finish, and very near crying if he were a bit long you know, but - that's how we spent our Sunday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 There were some children who didn't go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Oh a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well there were lots of people, you see there was - people that - didn't believe in churches at all there. Oh lord, aye. And mind one time we had a tremendous lot of Catholics, Irish people living there. When th
ey came to build this Cardiff railway. And there were - lots of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 There was no Catholic church up there was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no, no, no, no. There was only - there was - English Baptist, Welsh Baptist, Methodist - what's the other one, I don't kno
w what the other one was, Bethesda, and the church - that's right, and the church see. That was five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have different clothes for Sunday,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh Sunday - oh we had a - a good suit for Sunday and we never wear it any other day either. Of cours
e you - you know - do you know - what a little two piece flannel coat and flannel trousers used to cost in them days? How much do you think? Four and six. Four and six. Tuppence ha'penny for a tie. See? You could buy a brand new - well when you were a you
ng man twenty, twenty-two, I could buy a suit, measured, for twenty-five bob, and have a pair of shoes given in with it. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you play games on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, damn no, that wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Your parents thought it wrong did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - yes, yo
u could - oh yes, you could - you only done with - don't make any mistake, don't think I'm telling you I didn't play. You couldn't if your parents knew. Oh, we'd - get out and - have any - very - very often go and play tip tap at the windows you know and 
- in the afternoon, and people'd be going to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would they say if they found out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh - wouldn't - you wouldn't have hiding, no, but anyone said you'd been round - go on to bed, or they'd send you upstairs for an hour or two like you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents attend a place of worship or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh God, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Denomination?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Welsh Baptist. Baptist, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How often would they go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Every Sunday, three times a Sunday and in the week, prayer meetings oh lots. They wer
e -I didn't hear nothing about Sisterhoods in them days mind, never heard anything but there - there was a prayer meeting, a Band of Hope, and a night for a cantata you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Both your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. My mother was a great chapel work
er. If there was concerts or anything you know, she'd be selling tickets for weeks. To make it a - profitable business for the church. And she'd sew, making clothes for the different - parts in the cantata. She'd be sewing and making, oh yes, a good worke
r. And my father was a very de - devout man, and - yes, a good supporter, if they were going - make - do a cantata, he could see it - before he'd do it. And he used to work it out all in his brain, oh yes, chapel and church, they were - that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mentioned that you went to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye. Once a year. Well not every year. According to how the - finances of the church}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5393423\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 d be. And it would be - Landord Major, Barry, Sothertown. But
 the last outing I went to - one of the young girls had got married in the village, she was about twenty-four, married a wonderful nice man from Abercarn. Bill Thomas. And he had one little boy. And he came on this outing to Llandrid Major with us. And - 
i
t was a very rough sea, and that's the last outing I went oh, he went in the water and he got drowned. One of the Sunday school party. Aye. And - oh - dreadful, a terrible - dread - terrible thing that was. The men were there all night very near you know 
b
ut - but we used to go on - on - what was the other place we used to go to? Berlais, Always there in the Lais were a pub on the sands, and a - a farm close by, and about ten donkeys. Well, well, well. We'd be up and down on the donkeys - all day. And that
 went - the reason they'd go there because there was nobody had money to spend see You go there and - have two or three rides for tuppence or three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5393423\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
