pence a week. You could - you see - you were asking something - people didn't have the money to do those things. You had no money to do anything those days. You couldn't join any club to pay any money in , no, Never - and there were no clubs - d
rinking clubs like there are today, only pubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you get on with your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
I oh we were all lovely you know. Never no trouble with us, we were always - we were all together. If one was in trouble we were all in damned trouble, there was no question about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well my youngest sister see because - when she was born - I was a boy about twelve I suppose, and she was very delicate and she had St Vitus dance. And - well - 
we used to look after her, if she was - and she is up 'til today to be honest, well she's the only one alive now. See they're all - my - all my sisters are dead now barring her. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - I had - well I could - I couldn't tell you that because matter of fact - I used to play with everybody, everybody'd play with me.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye, my - oh and my brother didn't play much with him because - he was six years younger than me. Still, I looked after hi
m a lot you know. Oh aye. But we never played much together. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh Lord, aye, all my neighbours, the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In the woods. In the woods or in the field or on the road. Fo
otball on the road was the biggest part we played and - I - matter of fact, it's a funny thing you were asking me just now - a boy I played with for years, lived by me - he was a marvellous shot with a gun, and his father was a keeper at - Greenmeadow Est
a
te, and he came up with - last week, he comes up about once every four months, to spend a couple of nights up in - with his sister in the town, and we go to have a drink together, eighty-two years. Now you might know him. They kept the Wenbow Arms, John P
a
lmer. He's retired from there now. But if you go along that road to Barry, you'll see the market gardens, Palmers. That's his-his - that's the son. Well him and I, we very often - and last he was up here now - about three weeks ago, and I took him in my c
ar - up around the old woods where we used to go. And we called in the Black Cock and had a drink and - aye. Weal - very wealthy man he is now mind. But of course he's feeble, he can't drive a car. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you ever play in other children's homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh no, no, no, no. No, never go - we didn't do that in them days, you - your people in them days wouldn't have you in their houses. Out to play. Out to play wherever you went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would you do if it was raining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, well if it was raining we'
d go down the market or somewhere you know to play. Don't stop in the house do - do you if you can - go out of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You wouldn't go into other children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5393423\charrsid13850017 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 s houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no. No, no, no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What games did you play, you've mentioned a lot of them haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Ah yes, ordinary little games that you - play - cat and dog. That was a - I don' know whether you've ever heard of that have you? Cat and dog, that was a very popular game. Marbles was the most popular game. We played big ring and l
ittle ring. And - in - on the Whitsun Monday mind - oh God it was a - Whitsun Monday was one of the - greatest days in the year, We had a - five }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5393423\charrsid13850017 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 unday schools used to - go to the sports to the same field. Good God. Kiss in the ring, twos and threes. And not children mind. Women and men, 'til ten and eleven o'clock in the night. But th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5393423\charrsid13850017 ey}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  have all finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 If you did you had to damned well wash before anybody saw you. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes. Never know - never no restrictions about who you played with and - and I'll tell you something more. If there was any little bit of quarrel with somebody else - your parents never made you do what they done. If the
y were bad friends with anybody, you haven't got to be because they are. Oh no. No, no, they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. Play with who you like and do what you like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 There was no you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 ng}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  organisation them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 I'd like to ask you how you spent your free time while you were at school. You have mentioned a lot of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, well - I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Collect anything?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
No. No. Collect nothing - there was nothing - see - today if you understand me - there's - stamps - photographs - footballers. But there were nothing like that in them days. See there 
were - no professional footballers not then, there was nothing like that. The - the only thing you could do in those days - if you wanted to enjoy yourself - make your own enjoyment. Whatever you wanted to do I - I remember - when we were boys, a publican
 
- Dyke his name was, and - had a little pony, and we - Tong Fair came there, and we had a little shed down there, built a little shed, and we had a horse in there, and we're charging a penny each with - to go and see the horse with its head where its tail
 
ought to be. See? And would you believe me - the women and men were going in there and they wouldn't come out and tell anybody else that's what it - they'd be laughing you know and they'd let everybody - and what we had - the horses behind was in the mang
e
r and his head was by the door. But - oh things like that we'd do you see. And then we had another little pony and - used to - we used to say it'll tell the time. And the funny thing about it see - it would -if you said to it, come on Tommy what time is i
t. And he'd drag his foot like this. Oh we used to - the fun we used to have you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You said you did a bit of gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye, always done a bit of gardening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, I - well, when I say no - we used to go catch trout in the brook you know belonging to Colonel Lewis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Twelve year old. For a penny for the - of a man that had his leg off. Tom Bonner, Amy Johnson and all the big singers were coming down - to sing at five shillings a head. And it snowed the night 
of the concert. They didn't know what to do. So my father and mother now, and they were getting on by then, they had to take - over. And I can see my father and mother now. They sang a duet, John and Modwen. I couldn't sing it here now but it went somethi
n
g like this, What you a soldier? Never mind your satisfaction you - you'll fight for no one but for me. You've done enough to - oh damn, it drew the place down. They didn't want anybody else. They were there 'til - eleven o'clock that - in the night. And 
they were only amateurs you know, but oh - oh what. In the village we are talking about look - they had more talent there - than anywhere in the country. Beautiful talent, oh God. And - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You went for a lot of walks did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh a lot. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have a bike?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you go bicycling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 I used to go - all over the place, anywhere. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who did you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 A little fellow by the name of Ernie Roberts, we used to go - sometimes around - aroun
d - up around Caerphilly, down Mapham, onto the new foot road and back home. Oh we done a lot of bike riding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Oh I used to be a terror to play football and play cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 did you go to any theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no. The one, the Empire, aye. No, only the Empire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
No, after - after 19 - 12 we started to get about a little bit better but - then the war come, so you go - so never - you see - what people don't realize -
 but when you talk about the Whitsun mind - you see, we - there's no such a thing as Whitsun today. The Whitsun Monday we used to have now. From first thing in the morning, we'd be going around fetching the milk, down the shop getting the cake, the bread.
 
They'd be preparing all then one o'clock the march would be. And there would be how many of us there would be in the five churches. About five hundred marching with a band and - and with a band in front of 'em, everyone with their own banner. And every ki
d
 in the village - would have a new suit. Now - but in them days we kept a shop, my aunt did. And that's when a little two piece would cost - about four and six, flannel trousers and coat. And then -- we'd have - march around the village. And not a mile, b
u
t five mile right around. Then we'd go and have our tea. Five o'clock the band would come back down to the church, and we'd march down the field. And then we'd start. Sports. But - in them days - we'd march down the field , and there'd be sports, with pri
z
es and everything for the children running and racing, sack race, three legged race, then when it come - about half past seven to eight, now the dancing on the green. God. There would be hundreds there. They used to come from Aberdare, Abercunnon, everywh
ere. Everywhere, and - they'd be - dancing 'til eleven, twelve o'clock at night. Today they're going home at half past six. Well we had to make it in them days, we had to make -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you go to any concerts when you were still at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes. Aye, I - well - I remember going to - lots of little concerts we used to get in the village. Sixpence to go in, three}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 pence to go in, I was in a concert - when I were twelve year old, in a chapel called Bethesda, on a Boxing night. And come out from the conc
ert at ten o'clock, walking up to - by the square where the three pubs are, and saw a man got - another man killing a man right opposite us. Yes. That's right, yes. That - that were - tom Davies Oh lord alive, there were plenty of little - concerts in the
 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How about music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No music halls. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence a week - when you - on a blank day and sixpence on a pay day. Paid up -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How about when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh we had no pocket money then. Good God no. Be damned glad to get a - scrounge a ha'penny off anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh well - you were - aye, the children, all we children would help and do what we could. Oh - oh the neighbours were always good but they - you - no one would guarantee to come in to look - no neighbour would pass if they know anybody was ill mind. Oh no.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You said you were twelve years older than your youngest sister, do you remember when she was born? What happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 I - we were - we were in - I was a bugger to be honest with you. And we - I - we
 were - I was a devil of a boy to make wine and make - toffee and everything and bit of cake for myself, and my mother would buy the - and of course now I'm older - no bugger ever said my mother was going to have a baby. Nobody - don think she said a word
.
 And I come home - from somewhere this day and - my three sisters are sitting in the - in the house there. My brother said - do you know our mum is going to have a baby? Don't talk, so soft, I said. Yes. I said, don't be so soft, of course she isn't . But
 anyhow - she - the nurse is up there now. And with that I happened to - well, I said, listen to the little bugger screaming. Listen at the little bugger screaming I - oh aye, aye. And - mind -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How would she manage then when she was confined like that, who would help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh, damn they weren't in bed two days in them days girl. But they were - oh all the neighbours - all the neighbours would come in and - anything you want -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You wouldn't employ anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, you wouldn't employ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 nobody. And 
you wouldn't ask anybody to come in. They'd come. And oh they'd come in and - they wouldn't be saying - they used to call one another - Maggie and - Jennie. How is Maggie this morning then, kind of thing. Oh lord alive, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Sisters and brothers. And mother had - two brothers and one sister wasn't it. One sister kept the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How much did they see of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - see 'em every day practically didn't they, They used to pass - weren't v
isiting back and fore mind. Oh no. No. My uncle, one uncle I had, he used to visit up - he was living about a mile away, and he'd visit about once a week. But the others were living in the village, but they didn't - visit a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your father's people? Were they living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
They lived nearby but they never bothered. We never - they were - my - my - the - my father's two sisters were two old maids, and his only brother were an old bachelor. And he was a terror to booze, and he was a ca
retaker of the castle I told you. They never visited one another. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh God, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where did they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Everywhere. Their friends used to come to the house from Monday morning 'til Saturday night, an
d in - all this - surrounded by chapel work. See built - all this friendship is all - chapel work, there was no other - no other interest, it was - all centred around the church.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did they share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your mother have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, I don't think so, no. No - it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you father have any friends of his won?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, more or less open house - everybody'd come there - don't matter who they were, everybody was friendly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink if they came in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh God, aye. Oh lord aye. Aye, if - very little of course at that time but
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would it be on any particular days or occasions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, well I think it'd - more or less - in the evening
, or - although mind - on Sunday night - we did have a lot of visitors on a Sunday night. But - aye - we' all sit round the piano and - sing and bother, and even dance. And I was telling you about Christmas wasn't I? Oh - Christmas'd be the same but -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you say the friends invited in were your mother's friends or your father' friends or both of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 All the friends, friends of - everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh God, aye. Yes, lot of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Any time, any evening - it was open house any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes, any - well you see - oh God aye, and - if somebody went down the road and said - oh dear, I saw Maggie now, she don't look well at all. Oh, before ten min
utes go there'd be two or three - what's the matter Maggie, aren't you well then? See, this is the sort of - but there's none of that - none of that today you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well it is true. Yes, Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - what I think myself - and truthfully - I think that in - Wales, I don't know nothing about - but I think they - centred themse
lves - around music. All the people that I know in our village, there were no gossiping or anything else, there ware nothing to talk about. Without it was the church and the music. See, and they all centred themselves - they built a castle of the music in
 our village. See, this is what it was all - there were no gossiping of anything else
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was there a choir in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh lord, there was a ladies choir, a - male voice choir. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mentioned the band didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, and the band, the village band, aye. Aye, gosh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did they used to compete?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh - mind you see, understand - don't think that it - it were only church. We used to have - eistedfodds in the village, and big eistedfodds. See? A
nd we us to have - what do you call 'em now, the jazz band and that - church and - all that sort of stuff there. Carnivals and - oh, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
there be a village cricket team?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no, no, no, there were - village football team }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 nd. Oh God aye. rugby football was the pride of our village and we had the finest team in the country one time. Oh aye ,and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups. In that it before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one 
class or group and some to another?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh - oh yes. Yes. Yes, there were all - there were a lot of - there - there - if you understand me, the - now I - I don't like to say this. I don't like - In my opinion see - the church people - would try to keep 
their - selves apart from the rest of the village. Oh yes. Oh yes, and - and - it - it isn't a matter of feeling it, it was true. If a person went - of course Colonel Lewis, the Squire of the village, was a church man. And in them days you see - those peo
p
le that went to church - thought they were nearer the Squire and he was their - if you understand me, their God. They thought they were nearer - to the Squire than we were. They were bigger shots. Oh yes. There were two distinct different class of people 
in the village. Oh yes. Oh lord aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What would you say they were now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well I - I will tell you what I - I would like to tell you I daresay, but I will turn on to tell you that - if I wanted to put 'em in their - political - they were - Conservat
ive party people, and the - ordinary Liberals. That's what I call them. And they were no doubt about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What group would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 The Liberal people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What sort of people belonged to the same group as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Good honest working class people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What sort of people belonged to the other class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
People that like to get all they could for bugger all. That's the class of people - more - aye, more moneyed people, that's the class of people here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were you ever told to touch your cap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Show respect in anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. But I did do that mind. Oh yes. I did do that to the S
quire of the village. And although - until - although the people - the ordinary people in the village - well tripe I call them, would try to copy Colonel Lewis Tremeadow. They never copied him because he was a proper gentleman. I always Colonel Lewis Trem
eadow if he come on the road or - always saluted - and Lady - Lewis. Because -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Why do you call him a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Because - if you waked a bit of help or a bit of advice - held always do it for you. And I'll tell you something more. If he kne
w - that you were genuinely - ill and couldn't work and had - didn't have a bit of meat, you'd have a bit on a Saturday. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You weren't told to take your cap off to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no, no. No. No, no, no. And if you ever got in any trouble you see
. He'd help. I re - well I - here - here for instance now. One time when I was quite a young man - his son formed - a - bit of - crowd - crowd of people they called them the Glamorgan Guides. Captain Harry Lewis. And he had one chap in it, and he were fro
m
 Tapswells you know the one, you know, Jack - Jack Evans. And we're walking to Whitchurch one night, and he's coming up on his bike in his uniform. And my two friends are in front, and they asked old Jack Evans, got a match Jack? And he went like that you
 
know. So they looked back at me and said, stop him Griff. So I went and I pulled him off his bike. Ripped his trousers and - he went to Captain Harry Lewis and he sent for me. So - I went up to see Colonel Lewis. And he said, what did he summons you for G
r
iffiths? So I told him the whole story. Huh. Damned foolish that any damned fool - he give me a letter - to go to court. And he were a magistrate himself. When the- Cap - his son now - had a solicitor defending the - when they had me up now and - Bullock 
t
he solicitor was giving me a bad name for hitting this boy, I give this letter to the Clerk of the Court. And - Clerk of the Court give it to the magistrate and he said - Bullock, he said - you can't know this boy, he said. I've got a letter here from - o
ur magistrate, he said, Colonel Lewis, who says that he's a wonderful good boy. That - now you can see what sort of man he was. His own son prosecuting me - for upsetting - and him getting me off. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You'd cal him sir would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was there anyone else you called sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh damn no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Anybody you called master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 By taking their cap off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, oh lots' of
 people. Oh - yes. In them days, aye, I mean if you when you lived in our village and you were courting a young man, and I passed you, I'd raise my hat to you. Oh that was done a lot in them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In the district who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 In the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Or in the district. Who would you consider the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well that's a very - tough one to answer because there are lots of people - I thi are very important. I think myself that there are a lot of ministers of the gospel - that are very important people and very - very genuine people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 There'd be Colonel Lewis of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes. I think - he was always a very important man, in fact I would - but - the ministers of gospel, some of - not all of 'em
. Some of 'em. And some of the vicars mind. Although you had - but Colonel Sewis and his wife - I thought they were some of the most important people - in the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Why were they considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well because - they were - as type of peo
ple - that was always out - although they - were the station above you, and they were - they were always out to help you if they could. They wouldn't do you a bad turn - if you did a bad turn yourself - they wouldn't do it back to you. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When you say some of the ministers why do you consider them important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well because some of the ministers are very genuine people. good men. And I'll tell you one thing. I don't know how to tell you this, but there's one man in the village - same as me, went
 to school with me - and I look up to him today you know. I look up to him. He was brought up with a family of paupers. His mother used to bake bread - all the children became }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 hristians. Some of them became schoolmasters. One had been abroad, I don't know
 - big shot he is. Bu this one brother was a schoolmaster in Whitchurch. Ha lives here now. And he'd been - a pillar of strength in the village. When that little - church th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 at}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  they go to, I remembered - only his family, open - keeping it open. His family a
lone marching onwards. And they fought and fought, they tried to close the church - I don't know how many times. But that family kept it open. And he's a - what is he today there. Seventy-six today. But a sick man. Wilfred Thomas. Now1 always looked up to
 
him. I always looked up to him. He became a -he rose from the ranks - of a private, to a Major in the Army. And they - his - his platoon used to worship him. They'd do anything, go anywhere with him. And he went all through the war. Aye. Now then. I remem
b
er when Armistice Day come - and they had a big parade in the village. And Colonel Lewis of course - always took the - took the - head, but this is the one time that I really - felt sorry for Colonel Lewis. Because this Wilfred Thomas - took the head of t
h
e - he had been all through the war and he was a Major. And he took the head of the parade - procession, and I think that was a terrible hurt - for the old Colonel mind, although he never said nothing. Oh no, he was second in command that day. Oh yes, I t
hought -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you come into contact with Colonel Lewis?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 And with the ministers I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes, well I - I'll tell you a little story about Colonel Lewis now. One of my pals - had an accident with his foot - William Robert. Trolley
 went over his foot. So of course - there were no hospitals in them days, couldn't go to hospital. So he smashed his foot. Doctor then, he had him in bed. So of course he had to get a - bedpan. So - the only way - couldn't buy one because didn't have the 
m
oney, go down to Colonel Lewis and borrow a bedpan. So they went down to the Colonel Lewis to borrow a bedpan. So me and my three pals now and their pals, went down to fetch this bedpan. And there's a private path - going from Tremeadow up around the back
 
you know. So goes in there and Sharp the butler, oh you come for that bedpan have you, Griffiths? Yes sir. Right. Brought the bedpan - pan out in a bit of brown paper like you know. As we come out from the house, take the brown paper off and I put this be
dpan on my head you know, and we're larking about, some bugger threw a stone and hit the spout off. I had to take it back to Colonel -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - now what little bugger done this, the Colonel said, you know. But he give us a new bedpan. Oh aye. But oh dear -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about the shopkeepers, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - a shopkeeper in the village - oh - like the old fashioned type you know. Like the old fashioned type.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Everybody, oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about the clergy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh they'd mix with everybody too. Yes, well - well you see the clergy, and the shopkeepers - there were no question about - it - it was their job, they had to keep well in with all the people and they all mixed togethe
r. There were no snobbishness, only with a certain clique - of Conservatives. And they were - oh - you know, they -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well they were - painters - decorators some of them were, and - a couple of clerks from the - Cardiff, and - a
nd - Paine and Viljoen, they were all - schoolmasters now, that was another one. They always thought they were better than somebody else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who did the teachers in the village mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - in them days - we only had about four teachers there, 
because - half of the village had to go to Tapswells to school see. Because there were two parishes, Eglasilon and Whitchurch, and we in Eglasilon all had to go to Tapswell. The schoolmaster and about three teachers. But - the two teachers lived near Whit
church, so there were only a master and one teacher living in the town and they mixed with everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any farmers around?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh lord, aye, we had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - the - the pubs. Always in the pubs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What sort of people would you say went to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh the ordinary rank and file. Oh the church you mean, oh no, no, no. No. No. Well - I - it's a job to - job to - explain the people that went to chu
rch, I - I - it's people like - but - didn't actually work for - anybody else, but they sort of - had some little sort of jobs - for themselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mean working on their own account?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 That's right, and - schoolteachers, and their wives, or - of
fice - staff, and their wives. We used to think they were a little bit above - the ordinary people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about the people who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh - all classes, everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any who didn't go anywhere at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Who would they be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
There was a lot - there was a lot - of people - didn't go at all but - they were not the people of the village, they were people that - came into the village. People of the village - from the littlest to the biggest, all went to chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You mean these people who came in were the Irish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Irish people and came in to work and to build you see. Make the tracks and build the railway. But they - they were more of - a boozer on a Sunday. But - oh - all the villagers went to chapel. Do you know -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 But the pubs weren't open on Sunday were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes, of course they were. Yes. Do you - I remember now when I was - twelve or thirteen year old - my Uncle Jim - and his four pals used to go - they were trams, and they'd go in at
 half past twelve and they'd sit down having a drink. And - when the church bell would go - leave their drink, straight into church. They'd come out of church. And they'd go for a walk. Down to Whitchurch, call in the Hollybush, call in a pub here called 
- the pubs are open all day then girl. Yes. All day. And then there was another class of - pub, when they closed then - for - three mile - mile limit, do you remember that? See well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You could demand something then if you walked three miles couldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - well, aye, and - who knew, they wanted to walk from Whitchurch from the Hollybush up the Tong. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living, or would you say there were different groups?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh no. They were all - more or less - of course - understand me - all our families - kept a lot of pigs. All the people in the village. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You all lived the same way did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 That's right, we all had our little bit of bacon and th
at, see whether you liked it or whether you didn't, that was the main bit of food that we used to have in them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you think that one group felt superior to the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. The - no, only in - professional way. Like - aye, and - and - and a
part from that - now there were - three classes - of musicians. See? And there was a lot of jealousy - among the three classes. Now my sister - was a - marvellous singer. Now there was another lady there, she were a marvellous singer too, a soprano. And t
h
e - the enmity between the two. My sister was a contralto. She'd go on, she'd win something, now the other one wouldn't sing against my sister. See, oh no. And all the time when my sister went to South Africa, there was a lot of - lot of enmity, wasn't th
ere then. Lot of enmity abut - with the - with the professional singers and the choirs and that. Oh - oh a lot. A lot of competition.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. Not in our village. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember a distinction between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh aye, there was a - yes, yes. See - in them days - we had some craftsmen, like what you - don't see today, a stonemason. And first class }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 carpenters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 . Now my grandfather - was a first class - class ca
rpenter and a cabinet maker. Used to turn the legs of chairs and - and all that. And they were looked upon - as - as something a bit extra, to what other people were. Oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, I think they did, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, I don't think she did. No, I think my - well I couldn't - my mother was one of the nicest women in the world, she - every
body was her friends and she had no particular class to be attached to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, I mean - if you went to church - and now I mean this - you were just going to church, you'd be years
 before you'd be one of them. Oh - not like today mind, today -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember anybody who did sort of go from one class to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, yes, I remember a - people coming to live in the village - the Jones are on top of the hill and they 
went to church, they were going to chapel, and they were a bit lah-di-dah, and then they - went into the church with the church people. But they didn't stop there long because - they weren't made enough of. See, there's a certain class of people they join
 a - an organization - to be mad something of. But they were never made anything of so they came back to the church they came in the first place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye. Always around girl. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh lovely. Lovely. There was no talk with him, if we done something wrong he'd give you a clip under the ear or a boot in the backside and that was the end of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would your mother threaten you with the policeman if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. How many - he has many times but it didn't make any difference. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Rented, oh - oh yes. No, the - no, the first - well until we bought the house at the Mill - at the top of the hill. We bou
ght a house up there then. Aye, mortgage, we - we had to pay the mortgage every week, it's just like rent isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you see anything of the landlord when it was rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you remember feeling your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, many times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you think about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well - I used to worry a lot sometimes but - we got to know that there was no good to worry about it, all you could do was do your best to help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh a damned lot of difference. A lot of difference, lot of things we couldn't have that we had - ought - ought to have and - a lot of time we had to sit in the house that we couldn't go out. Oh aye
, sat in the house many a time because we didn't have a suit to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you feel about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well I mean it was one of those things, it was something that you had to put up with, you had to - do what you could do and that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How often would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well very often, don't bother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What difference did it make when your father was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well, the point - the point is we had to go without - quite a lot more than - we didn't - have - have much at - in the 
best of times. But we had to cut down on that even. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you ever get help from the Guardians or the parish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no. No, if you asked for it you only get half a crown a week, it wasn't worth having. No. The thing we used - I'll tell y
ou this now, if you didn't go out to work, we always dealt in a shop, and you'd go and get in that shop, and when you started work you started to pay it back. That's how you had to live whether you liked it or whether you didn't. And you - in debt in lots
 
of shops, clothes, shoes, and your bit of groceries. But - what my mother always impressed upon was this. When times is bad and my father out of work, there were no money coming in, let's eat the cheapest we can eat, as long as we could - bones and make s
t
ews, and we'd do without - if a shirt was broke, all right, put a bit of needle and cotton in it, mend it. Couldn't afford to buy new and she wouldn't buy new without it was - bound to, it had to be bound before she'd buy if the money wasn't coming in. An
d of course I - I - I'd very often think you see - there's lots of things I puzzle about now, in them days the railway men - a pound a week, nineteen shillings a week, and yet - the - there's som}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  of them just a couple of years older than me, yet - they hav
e all died and left wonderful bloody property and money, where from? Out of a guinea a week. Isn't it - marve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
lous where they got it from? But mind what we did do what they don't do today - we always had allotment. And - and you're telling me, and don't - 
you think now, packet of seeds for a penny, lettuce. Gosh, you'd have - seventy or eighty lettuce there. And we - used to eat 'em then, but they don't do it today. Pigs, always kept pigs see, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of very strongly, was there any special way in which they showed it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh yes, they never used to - wouldn't allow 'em in the circle, wouldn't allow 'em in any - they wouldn't - now, for instance, fi there were a poor person there, nice p
eople and Whitsun come and they had no money - they would club around the village to buy the kids clothes, to go to Whitsun treat. But if they disliked anyone - finished. They didn't ever want nothing to do with them. And anybody do anything - to anybody 
in the village, a stranger I mean now that come there, they might as well go from there. They'd never be taken up - taken to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did they ever make people leave the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, I remember a - what they call drummer a person out, I remember -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Tell me about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
I remember a - a person, I re - remember a person coming there - to live in a - very select part of the district. And they had been there - oh - three or four months, and the woman - and her two daughters and a man. But - there
 were a lot of talk going around that there were other men - coming back and fore there. Well anyhow one of them - members of the church lived close by her. And one day - he happened to be coming out and he saw this man - going in there. And the other one
 
coming straight out. And - one of the girls came out on the door and didn't see him - and told her - her sister - our mam'll have to stop it because people are watching her now. This is the five - fifth men - man has been here today. Well of course she wa
s
 - using the house for immoral purposes. So they drummed 'em out. Crowd of people - crowd of people - crowed of people come there with old tins and that, knock - stood around their doors knocking and shouting, get out, get out. And the next day they'd gon
e
. Oh aye, aye. Oh I've seen that happen twice. Yes. Aye. Same thing, a - no. A woman - the first black man ever - come to - a girl married a black man. Well she said she married him but she didn't. She came - brought him there to live, with her mother. A 
l
ittle tiny cottage, only two rooms it was, and her mother would live in the back top of garden, and she brought this black man here. They drummed her out. Same thing up there, all the - and - see they'd get the children of the village to come into it see.
 All the children would come around there and - bang on tins and - anything you had you know and shouting, get out, get out you dirty scout and all this kind of thing. Aye, that's the two lots we had from there. Oh -
