\insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 oh Howell Griffith}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
. That'll do. Don't ask you whether you done it. Come here, and away you'd have it. But min we - used to play hell with them two, don't bother. Oh - didn't have it all their own way. 'Cos we were big boys like you se
e. I remember on a Christmas the schoolmaster said - if you boys can bring a fir tree up - bring it up. We goes in the plantation. And cut one of the fir trees down. Carried it up to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 
 the school. And - we had it al}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
put in ready for the Christmas. And the following morning we're all sitting in the class and the schoolmaster said to 'em - he said, you Tong boys, would you mind coming out here? We all went}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 out and he started to tell us if he - started on, he said, well now boys, he said - in school yesterday? 
Yes sir. Oh. I see you've got a lovely tree, now where did you want that from Arthur, to Bernie Arthur this is. Oh we cut it in the woods sir. Oh ah. What wood did you cut it in? I don't remember sir. Griffiths, what wood did you cut this tree in? Oh the 
plantation sir, but we thought it was one that was no good. Oh well - well you'd better go up and see the keeper of the forest and apologise for - taking one of the trees. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would the girls be punished the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would they be caned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Telling me. They were - Tapswell school were damned brutal in them days. They had some - Jerry Davis and - the - the the sloper, Tom Sloper, they were treacherous beggars. And they weren't very old you see. They were young men a
bout nineteen or twenty. I wouldn't call 'em teachers, today I suppose they'd call 'em - students. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh aye, aye, oh yes, they - oh they - more the girls than - than my brother and I. And
 - I - well let me explain this to you. They were damned a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
xious - in them days look - now my youngest broth - my brother, the only brother - we were so bad off, that my mother altered his certificate - four months for him to go to work to earn a bit of mo
ney. See, you had to do - they were waiting for us to go out to work to earn a bit of money. See you couldn't - you - you couldn't say to her, turn round and say well - they had to give - 'em a bit of education. Good God, they - we had no money to have do
ne nothing with. And - they were glad to get us to go to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes, aye, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would they visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would they meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. None of that, there was nothing like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes. Yes, yes. And yet mind - in Tapswell - there was a lot of - what I'd call the second class boys there. Awful good friendly nice, but they were b
usiness people. And they've all turned out, I mean - perhaps you've heard of Walter Williams, the estate agent, auctioneer, the old - all lived in Cardiff, well he was going to school with me. See big business people. Then there were Rhys Williams, that g
reat big grocers shops, they were all - families - office boys and all that sort of thing. Well we was the sloggers. Collieries and tin works, and quarries.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh lo
rd, aye, oh they had their favourites. I mean in - in - in - in - in the Tapswells school, the Tapswell boys - the ones I'm referring to now could do what they like. But the boys in the Tong couldn't look. Oh - that - that's right, be - because of - becau
s
e of what the - what Tong's - thought of see. I mean - there were not many - well I - let me think for a moment now. I don't suppose that there were more than - a half a dozen - men - or boys living in the Ton, that wasn't working that - that had a office
 
job or anything like that. We were all tin workers, quarry workers or - or colliers, or - railway. There were no - they-wouldn't have no second class people here. It was all done to earth working men. And of course you'd see us - coming home working night
s in the morning, little short shirts and under our arm white aprons on. Sweating. I have seen this look - failing to walk home with cramp. See? Aye. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you feel the teachers then gave different treatment to some children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Oh they did, there's no question about that. Oh lord alive no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh aye, aye. Aye. Well we - let's put it this way. The gang in the Ton boys and the Tapswell boys. Aye, and - and we - undoubtedly if - let'
s put it this way, that of the two - we were the rougher - lads see, they were - sort of mamby-pambsy boys like a - office boys - men's children and - tried to be brought up like a second class people and we were - fight and rough and tumble see and - we 
could always give 'em a hiding if we want, and that's why I think - that the teachers always got a bit down on us. Because they knew that as far as we were concerned - we could hold our own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Were there any children who were left out of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh 
yes. Oh yes. There were a - they built a place called Moy Road. And a crowd of people came there - to live. Oh from everywhere. Everywhere, and nobody knew who they were, and they were a - dis - disagreeable lot. And you couldn't get on with them, and a d
i
rty lot. And a dirty - I remember for instance one time - my sister's coming home from school, and - my mother said, what the devil are you scratching for? And looked in her head - and she had some lice in there. No messing. My elder sister now next morni
ng - up to the school, who is she sitting by and - aye, no messing. And the girl she was sitting by was from Moy Road. And she was - full of 'em. Oh yes. And that -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Those children wouldn't be able to join in would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. Nothing, no, they - you were - and even when they were - cleaned up and that, they wouldn't take them no more. No, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you go on to another school after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Twelve. Passed the labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, I didn't want to. I - I - I'd have gone before if I could. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you attend any part time education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Ay? No. No, I can read, I can write and I'm one of the finest - counters in the world, you couldn't catch me for tuppence. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No. No. I think myself - that - I don't want to tell you this but - I'm a businessman 
before I came - here, and undoubtedly one of the finest businessmen around. All my own teaching, I think, I managed a Welsh sports in Castle Cave for eight years. No education. But I made a pot of money there. Oh - no, no. I - I'd - I've got to be honest 
with you and truthful to you. I don't believe in half this education. Don't believe in half of it. Now I get - that boy there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 While you were at school did you have any part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, in thos
e days - there were no little jobs of that kind, the only thing - we used to do - to earn a copper or two was to run errands for different women, go in the wood on a Saturday - and cut some sticks. Now - aye, now - mushrooms and the blackberrying. There w
ere no part time jobs, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well my first full time job was just when I was - twelve and a month. And I went to work in - at in works, Melingriffiths. And it was - from six o'clock in the morning - 'til six o'
clock in the night. And very very hard work. And you worked Saturday a half a day. And the wates then - was nine and four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have to work Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, no work on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. Gracious Lord no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well - you go down to the tin works and probably - you - you go there - twenty times - looking for a job, and then all of a sudden there'd be a vacancy - and we'd be about twenty or thirty looking for it. But
 - my father was working in the works and he'd been a bit - foreman there for years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 He was in that work was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 He was in that works. And so I had a little bit of a preference, over the other people. But - when the shops inspector came along - 
and he'd be there for a couple of days, you would have to go home then. Because you weren't allowed to st}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
rt in the works 'til fourteen. So - when we were star}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
ing at twelve, we were cheating and we had to keep out of the inspector's way, while he was there. But - you'd move on from there as the years go by - but it was harder work then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you actually have to do when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - in the - what they call the coal rows. They'd be - the bigger boys - boys about seventeen would be rol
ling the tin through the mills, and we'd be the other - other side - catching 'em and packing 'em up. We'd probably catch on an average - oh - about twenty pots a day. And there were no wasted - and no sitting down for breaks. You'd have your breakfast ti
m
e, you'd have your dinner time. And there were no spare time for twenty minute break or five minutes break. You worked right up 'til six o'clock. And you - and we used to walk a mile and a half to work in the morning, and a mile and a half back in the nig
h
t. Can you imagine how tired you were when you come - how tired you were. And I used to - a boy that was - I was working with - one of 'em anyhow, he lived on the bottom of the hill from me. I had to get up at five o'clock in the morning. Dress and walk d
own to his house - to have company to go - walk a mile and a half down the canal bank. Every morning. And there was no - holiday with pay.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You were paid nine and four you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 That's right, a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you feel it a fair wage or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well, yes, in those days there were not much - there were no trade unions about in them days like there are today you see. So - that was the only - job in the tin works, where you got paid a wage. See from there on - you were what we call a piecework. If 
you didn't earn it you didn't get none. And there was no such a thing as - going to work and you could get - two pound a week plus bonus. Oh no. You started off scratch. You earned nothing if you didn't earn - if you went to work - and working in the mill
s, and you - started to work six o'clock, something happened, you didn't work only five minutes, you wouldn't get no pay, if you stopped there all day. You had to earn what you - what you got. Piece work work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Give it all to my mother, you give your docket, you used to have a docket. Tell you how much you earned and - they used to keep tuppence out for the infirmary, and tuppence out for the doctor. But we had a works doctor. And - you had to pay those
 - whether you - liked the doctor or whether you didn't, you had to pay the doctor and the - and in the summer months as you get older - would have the c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 bs outside the works. When it was very very hot, the men'd be taken home in cabs with cramp. Oh God. T
here's no question about it, but - boys working from twelve - up to fifteen - hardest work I ever remember. Your hands were all cut and sore. The sheets of tin that you were handling - were like razors. You had leather pads on your hands. And only want to
 
make a little slip, oh you - and you've cut yourself to pieces. And - oh there were no - beg your pardon - if you done anything wrong out you'd go and there'd be thirty looking for your job. If you got out of work in them days - it was a devil of a job to
 
get another job. And then I removed on from there, you - went what they called policing in the cold room, catching in the cold rooms. Then - roughing - in the cold holes. Then you moved onto the mills. This - is a job. You work eight hours here. But you h
ad no - this is - where you start to work, with no pay without you earn it. Piecework. And - catching, we used to get - mind - in those days }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  tin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 working - was a trade mind. It wasn't a - ordinary labouring job. Skilled job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You went in as an unskilled boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
That's right, but you - and as you were going along, you get skilled, because - what they call catching in the tinworks. Was the first job. And in them days mind you got one and five - a dozen. If you done what we term - a dozen boxes, your w
ages for that time was one and five. Well - we used to do on an average - six - or seven dozen a day. Sometime more. Well you work it out now, six dozen a day. You see, there's nine bob. Isn't it? Well you work - six nines. There's two pound fourteen a we
ek. But some of the men was earning five pound a week because - they were getting three and - three and seven a - a dozen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well because - they were ; gone higher up than you are. See the catcher - is the lowest job in the mills. Furnace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 man is the next lowest job. But - in those days there was four men to a mill. A furnace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
man. A roller. A catcher. And a doubler. But today - or at least - before the works closed down, there were seven men in a mill. Three men what they called helpers
. They used to help 'em all. So they're all getting - their twenty minutes or - quarter of an hour break every hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 It's very hot isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Very hot then. Little - that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 About the proces}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  in the tin works.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 The furnace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 man used to put it out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Aye. Is that on now. Well see the furnace - the furnace}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 man - would fill his with - coals and sheets. And when they'd get red hot - he'd - then we'd start to work. He'd pull it out red hot, a piece probably weighing about -
 twenty - eight or thirty pound. Throw it to the roller and that piece would probably - be a yard long. Now when the roller would have it he'd shove it in the mills, the catcher behind it would catch it, shove it back to him and he'd shove it in again, an
d
 probably the third time, then it'd come out - probably about three yards long. See? Then they'd throw that to the doubler, now of course it's getting a bit colder. The doubler would open the middle sheets, what they call doubles and fours, then he'd doub
l
e it up, cut the end off so - they were making eight sheets out of that. See now when they bring the eights out, they'd double them up again, the doubler would, and they'd make sixteen sheets. Well - after the day was finished, all those sheets would be p
u
t in one big pile and the cutter would come now and he'd pick 'em up - the shearer they call him, and he'd cut 'em into different sizes. Twenty - eight by twelve, fourteen by - all that sort of thing. And then the next morning - the women would have 'em. 
A
nd that's - their job would be - they'd be in sixteen sheets or eight sheets, they'd have to open 'em - all it - now - if the roller - wasn't a very good roller, and he had 'em - either too hot - they'd be stickers. So when the poor old women would go to 
o
pen 'em, it'd be hard work. But - if the work was what they call good work, they could open 'em like wink you know. And they'd be - sent up from there - into what we used to call the wash house. There they'd be washed, and dipped in metal, and they'd come
 
out silver. Beautiful silver sheets. And then they used to - in some of 'em - they used to - pack 'em - into - into tin and into a wooden box and all the tin that they were packed into would be soldered right about around, because this lot would be going 
t
o India, and they couldn't drop them anywhere, only in the water. So they were safeguard 'em not to get wet, they'd have to come to the water - when the tide went out to get them. And it was very interesting to see 'em doing that. But then you'd carry on 
-
 when you were working nights, you'd go on and you get - some of the mills were driven by water - some by electricity. And the water mills in the summer - they'd start at six o'clock. And they'd work like blazes - 'til about eight. Then you would have to 
h
ave a quarter of an hour spell or twenty minutes. Because - the mill would be going so slow, there wasn't enough of water to take it. So we'd have to put the gates up, and wait now for the feeder to fill again, so they'd have full of water then off we'd g
o again. And that's how you'd work during }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 the summer. But in the steaming}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
, where the - driven by engine, and they fixed up - big pipes, twelve inches - wide, to bring air, and they had big fans all through the works. To blow air down onto the men, when they were working.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 So they were better?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
A bit better, but it was tremendous hot. Oh, I - it was one of the hottest jobs, all you had was the trousers a pair of shoes and a little short shirt. And then - he men used to get cuts - and burns. And - th
ere were no beg your pardon, you'd have a burn or a cut - but you'd have to struggle to go to work the next morning. And it was like fighting for your life. There was twelve mills where I worked. And there was some very good men. Good workmen you know. An
d
 we'd be coming up from the rear sort of thing. And we'd come on tonight and they'd say - Ned Bowler done - eighty-two this morning. Now we'd struggle now - to try to do eighty-two you know. Sometime you could you do it and sometimes you - it was fighting
 
- for your life all the time. But what I got to say there was never all this - big money taken out of your wages. If you earned three pound or four pound, you only bit of stoppages would be - about sixpence or a shilling. Not like today. You're paying abo
ut two pound out of your pay today, for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, very happy crowd of people you worked with. There was always - always plenty of - always plenty of fun see, I remember - we had - min
d you there were such men as - a man who used to sweep the floor, and they were what they called labourers. A guinea a week. And I remember one man, and the funny thing now - his relative is living across by here. And he - working in the works, a labourer
 
he was, and he was going to get married. Now he used to pull your leg you know. Well what are you going to do when you get married, how much wages you going to give her? Oh, you - don't worry, he said, but he says - anyhow he got married and - on the firs
t
 Friday night he had his pay, and we were pulling his leg. Oh, he said, I don't know what I'm going to do yet. Well when he got to the house, he decided to give him wife the pound, and keep the shilling. And when he come to work Monday morning, he was bor
r
owing a cigarette and - he had no money, he had nothing. So on the Friday he was very - miserable all the week. So on the Friday we were pulling his leg so bad - he went home, and as he got to the house he thought, oh, I'll have to alter this. So he gave 
h
is wife the shilling and kept the pound. And his wife said to him - what am I going to do with this? And he looked at her and he said, well I was in the same boat last week. And - you know, the fun we used to have. Coming home from work - working two - si
x
 'til two, beautiful canal bank we're coming up, and all wild ducks - in the pond. And we - tired as we were - we'd be over in the bog, throwing stones to get a wild duck. And you'd bring him you know as a treat to yur mother. But I didn't like - a bit fi
shy they were to taste like you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well - very strict. Oh God yes. Strict. I mean you - there were no nonsense in - W.R. Davis were our manager, and - Thomas his - tinworks, they were the owners, but he was a v
ery strict man. And the old W.R. used to wear a box hat you know, come down through the mills, and he'd be looking round the floor, walking down he wouldn't think he'd seen anybody, but he didn't miss a thing. If there was somebody doing something out the
 
way by here, and he'd be looking down, he'd say, Davis come here a minute, what are you doing there? He'd see you in a minute. Oh - mind - as long as you done your work and you were a good workman you were appreciated. We had an old chap there, Toff Robin
s
, and used to count - the boxes when they were dried, one five twos and two four fours, and he was a bit of a foreman but he couldn't read nor write. So the manager said to him - Tom - pop around and check up how many one five twos we got will you? Yes si
r
, he said. And bring it up the office to me. So Tom ran off, full of himself now of course. Going around now, and - had a bit of paper in his - asking everybody what it was. So up the office he went, there you are sir, he said. This is what I got. Thousan
d
 boxes. So he give him his paper he had on the boxes. One hundred. One hundred you've got here Robins. No, he said, a thousand boxes sir. Somebody had told him there was a thousand - thousand there. Well he said, look Robins, he said, one and three nought
s
 - or two noughts is a hundred. Well a thousand it is sir he said. Well if it's a thousand, Robbins, he said - it's one - and three noughts. Oh damn, Mr Davis, he said, who'd have thought a little ought like that would have made all that difference. And t
h
at - that's genuine like, I don't know - and old Davis like was only a lad. We had another man working there - and he worked hard, one of the hardest working men, he was a little bit on the mental side, but one of the hardest working men in the works at a
l
l. He done more work in a day - than thee men'd do. But - but very often - and they wanted some water - to clear the deck. And the canal was by the side of - so they said to him, go and get a couple of buckets of water Tom. Two buckets of - out he goes to
 
canal. Put the two buckets down to get the water, when he went to lifts them up they pulled him in. And he's standing in the middle of the canal with the two buckets holding up like this - shouting help. And one of the bosses run out and a couple of the o
t
hers. Come on Tom, throw the water out. Oh damn, he said, waste it after getting it is it? In the middle of the canal. And those things that - those things are true about this you know. But oh - and then there was another job you move up to the - well, wh
a
t they call the wash house. Really wet. Now then, this job - they - they'd - you wouldn't get nobody to do it today. They used to put the - tin in the pickling - for cleaning purposes. Then it - they'd come out - soaking wet and they'd be put on a trolley
.
 And they had to be wheeled from here - well about - two hundred yards up into the wash house, wet dripping all in a little line, and the man that was doing the job had overalls, old leather aprons on, and - all leather - he - before he'd start an hour, h
e was soaked through to the skin. And he'd work eight hours like that. All - sacks around his leg. And that job - was twenty-five bob a week. They called that wheeling wet. Could you imagine anybody doing that job today?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you go through all these jobs yourself or what did you actually do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well I went through the cold rows. I went through the mills, and I went through the kneeling. Now the kneeling is a place - where - all the men - the - tin - are put into great iron - boxes. And put into the 
furnace for eight hours, and this is damn hard work. It is hard work. To a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 knell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
 the plates, to get 'em soft or hard whatever you wanted to. I worked there. I went all through the mills. And I went iron cutting. And that's another hard job. Iron cut - you 
cut all the iron that comes in in the long bars. For the men to have in the mills. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you feel about your employer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh well - let me tell - put it this - to you this way. You were glad to be employed. And we couldn't afford - although
 mind - never mind about couldn't afford - they would do nothing very dreadful to us. You had to earn your money and that was the end of it. I mean if you worked and earned your money, your bosses were good. Oh yes, I wouldn't call the bosses - but you ha
d to work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh, well in those days - we were glad to be there and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 \endash }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  tin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
workers mind were looked up to in them days. Oh yes, if you - it - it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 A lot of the work was skilled wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 See a lot - w
ell the biggest part of it was skilled see. From the minute we left the cold rows, it was all skilled. And - and it was something to learn as well. Oh there's lots of people went from my place - to - Italy. A lot went from there to India. You see, and the
y got some tremendous money. Oh and there was a tremen -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you like the work or did you dislike it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Yes, no, I liked - I liked to work all right. Yes, I enjoyed it. And - dear there was some very old - old men working there in the old mills. Se
e the little water mills - put me a - it - it was what I would say - convalescent. Because they'd have the old people working there, and they'd do about twenty boxes or twenty-four, where we were in what they called the steam mills and the new mills. And 
w
e'd be doing our sixty, seventies and eighties. But those old men, there was old men there - hardly able to stand you know. Could stand the heat all right. Been at the job for donkeys years, and they could go on paddling quietly, and the bosses would neve
r
 sack them. No. They never told you at Melingriffith you were too - you were too old to work. If you could do your job - doesn't matter how old you are, you could stop there. And there were some very old men there. Very old men. Over sixty-five, yes, men 
- but as I told you they were - if you understand me, it was more or less - a convalescent, they could - go - aye, and - and they - and there's nobody coming to 'em saying, now come on, get a move on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How long were you there altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Twelve years. Yes. Twelve years. Army from there. Yes. And then when I come out of the Army -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 When did you come out of the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 19 - the end of 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What did you do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Now I - married, I - was in - which I told you I got married then. And
 I went to a little place called Tonyrefail. And then was a job. Of all times to try to get work it was then. You couldn't get work anywhere. And I didn't feel after being out in the open - I didn't feel like going back to the colliery - tinworks, so I we
nt to the colliery. And - I never was a fitter. But I applied for the job as fitter, now I knew a lot about - fitting. And I got a job as a fitter there. Well - I finished up - in the coke ovens there, years after - as a first class fitter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How long were you actually in the colliery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 For eight years. Yes. And then I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh don't worry, when I come out - come - I come out from the Army before the war was over. And when I went to look for a job there - the boss sai
d, well I'm sorry, he said - all I'm looking for is fitters. So I knew a bit about fitting so I went up to the village - Tonyrefail the next day, bought the dungarees, went down two or three days after, looked for a job as fitter. And I had a fit - a job.
 
But I - there was a - they would give me a labourer. And I can remember his name now, Tom Jones. And he was a - better fitter than half of 'em - was there. So more or less I was a fitter but he was a fitter and I was the labourer sort of thing you know. A
nd it didn't take me long to to get into the stride of the thing then. But it was a very dangerous job, we were taking some very big tanks and big stills down. Very dangerous job it was, and hard work. But nothing like the tinworks mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What exactly did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Well - all the piping going around the - all around the colliery, and the benzel tanks, we had to renew all new piping, any little - pumps that was broke, repair pumps, but there was stills, what was call - what was - oh a section 
I should think, would be about a ton. And they were - ten sections on top of one another. And they were to make sulphur and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 ammonia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  and salt. And every so often we had to take them down for them to be cleaned. And there would be about - eighty nuts and bol
ts around one section. Have to have a big crane derrick up to get 'em down, and you'd be on that job probably for about a - two months you know. Taking 'em down and rebuilding 'em back. Oh a lot of hard work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well we wor
k - we used to start then at six in the morning. Finish at five. Hour to dinner, hour to breakfast. Then we - the eight hours come in. We were working eight hours, six 'til two. But in the - fitting line -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about Saturday?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh gosh, aye. And Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have any half days in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
No. No. Saturday and Sunday, and no half day at all. And then of course - after you had finished there - everybody had their own garden in those places. And you'd be in the garden, and they could 
come and call you out - to - oh yes, when you're on the coke and a fitter - anything go wrong during the night they could come and call you out and you'd have to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you have holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No holidays with pay. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What were you paid then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well, in those days the wages was - roughly about four pound a week. Yes. Four pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No, fair, no. See - the colliers mind - were getting a lot more than that see because they were getting - you w
ouldn't remember this - Buxton award. Sankey award. L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
oyd George award. They were getting three shillings a day - for those awards, whether they worked or not. So - you work 'em out, they were getting - five awards - fifteen bob a day - for five days a wee
k - so if - if they didn't go to work, that was coming in, but we - fitting that didn't get the Buxton award see. Nor the L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
oyd George award. Because we were working - day }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  day}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4881359\charrsid13850017 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 work as fitters.
