l out - by Saturday. It doesn't mean any harder work. But it means working - regular. Oh, yes, they'd do it, how much it worth? The first thing - now wouldn't you think that if - if a company's in trouble, and it's not costing you anything - you can put a
 little bit of an effort in to help out can't you? But they were never prepared to put a effort of any sort in without they were getting something for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Why do you think that was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well because it was covetness on the part of men. Not the men. The trade union officials. To make themselves }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017  big}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
shots. Same as - they're doing the same thing today. Do you hear 'em asking for two pound a rise? They're asking today for ten pound rise. But they don't realize - that you and I pay for that rise. Oh yes,
 I - of course they do. I - I - I've got to be honest with you and tell you this, I worked in places - and the people have been - well for instance, when I worked on the Western Welsh now I will give you this, I was - conducting. And I was a good conducto
r
. And I had - a lot of friends in in - influential - parts. We wanted a service - from Pentarch to Craigor. Now I was big friends - with a magistrate in Pentarch, Mr John Phillips, and he was a - him and I were good friends. So the Western Welsh tried for
 
this - route, and they turned it down, the - commissioners wouldn't give it to 'em. So John Phillips who lived halfway up the hill. So I used to stop the bus by his door. There were no stop there, to pick him up and bring him down, and the management of t
h
e - of the - bus firm knew. So we're sitting down one night him and I coming up. So he said, oh, how did you get on about the - extra service, he said, Howell? I said, they've turned it down. No, he said. I said, yes. And James was the commissioner. Well,
 
he said, why didn't you tell me, Howell? Well, I said, I didn't think. Oh, he said, I'll - see to this for you. How many buses you want to run there? I said, oh only five a day. Leave it to me, he said. On the following - Monday - he came to me and he sai
d
 have you got your - timetable made up for - I said, no. Get one made up, he said, it's starting next Monday. So - you know, back down into the office. Saw the manager, Mr Grey. So I said - got a bit of news for you sir. Yes, what is it Griffiths? That se
r
vice from Pentarch to Craigor, I said. Oh yes, he said, they turned it down. Oh, he said, well - I've seen a gentleman friend of mine, I said, and you can start it next Monday. Well he jumped up in the air you know. What are you saying? I said, yes, it's 
a
ll right. So he said, so he called in now Williams the under manager. And so he - then he said, no, he said - well I said, here you are, look I said, ring this number. Tell him that Mr Griffiths is in here now with you. So Grey the manager now, he rung up
 
this number, and I was sitting down, I could hear him say, oh well I - I am please - would you mind calling in and having a word with us. And thank you very much and - oh I don't know what it was. So when he come off the phone he jumped and he - tapped me
 
on the back. Well, well, he said, beautiful. For a week after - I'm promoted to inspector. Now you listen to this. And not - ordinary inspector, area inspector, going around different parts, down your place, I worked on the bus - buses - Basset's buses, I
 
bought the Bassets buses - for the Western Welsh. Going around - checking up on the runs, so that we could buy any service that we could by. I was going back to Swansea and all over. And do you know that my own mates - they had a trade union there, what t
h
ey call 'em - they fought for twelve months - to get me off the job, because I was a junior hand. And they succeeded, but - old Grey said, I want you in the office Griffiths, he said, and he told James the organiser, and nobody'd have the job, he said, be
c
ause I'm not putting another man in - on it. So I had a job in the office, and he - the - although they got me out to get a bloke by the name of Seymour on the job, old Grey - scrapped the job, he wouldn't give 'em a job. So I finished with the firm after
. But you see - trade unions are all right - as long as they play fair. That's it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you feel that there were divisions of interest among workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh yes. Oh lord aye. I tell you what I did find out myself. That there were a certain class of w
orkmen - they called themselves - Socialists, they called themselves Communists, and in my opinion they're nothing only a lot of trash to ruin the country. That's my own opinion about 'em. I have never in my life - asked anybody - to get me a rise or get 
anything for me. If I thought I was entitled to anything, I'd go and put my case - and I'd get what I wanted ten times out of every eleven. No, I - I - I got no room for 'em at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers. Did you feel that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
Oh - no. No, no. No, you see, what you've got to realize is the - who - who who was trained craftsman? Now - look - what you got to - can remember - that fitters - were hardly known then. There
 have been more fitters on the road in this last seventy years - than ever in the world, because - before the motor car was on the road - what will you call - a fitter wouldn't - they didn't call 'em fitters, they were turners in the steelworks and the ti
nworks. You see, it's only of the late - sixty years - that you've got - such a greater number - amount of - fitters and all this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You didn't feel there was a division?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 No. No, no. No, lord alive, no, no, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well - no. I wouldn't think so. No I wouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about life at home after you left school, did you continue to live at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes, lord alive, aye, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 You were only twelve weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Yes. Well, no, I - I don't think so but - no, I couldn't say that. I - I think when - even when I left home, twenty-five I left home - no,
 I - I couldn't see a change and I didn't see a change in anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 What about your relationship with your brother and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Oh damn no, they never changed. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you - spend your Sunday any differently when you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7606694 HG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Wel
l, now you're asking awful - awful questions, yes, I - of course we did. Yes. I mean - let's put it this way, whether you - liked going to chapel or whether you didn't - you had to go. In - when you were young. But when you became - twenty and twenty-one 
and twenty-two - you never told your parents you wouldn't go. And you did go. But when you felt like it. See - you slided off. Quietly. But you never - but that doesn't mean to say - that we didn't believe in the Bible and didn't believe in religion.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14495273 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 Did you go at all, did you go in the morning or the night or did you go to Sunday school?
