e used to get a Conservative member there - speaking on a pop box in the village. And we'd get a friend of ours - a Liberal and put him on the other corner. They'd be both shouting together. But - when the day of voting came mind - we were very very keen 
a
nd - whatever party you were looking - you were working with - you would work, but it wasn't like it is today, where they've got motor cars and - to fetch 'em - you had to walk and I know people that walked two miles - in the winter and in the snow to com
e and vote. Oh yes, and - we used to understand a little bit about what we - I never forget when L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
oyd George brought the new scheme in. Ten shillings a week for four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence a week. Remember that, oh well you don't remember it, but that was a great thing. Th
at was one of the finest things that ever happened in this - to us in them days. And of course what did we have - I - I - what did we have, about - three hundred members wasn't it? Something like that, and their wages was about four pound a week. But - se
e
 they were all - doing other work as well as being Members of Parliament. But today - they're all getting - sixty and seventy pound a week, still doing other jobs, and not so damned good as the people that we had in Parliament in them days. See this is th
