ere a boy from twelve year old, let's go on from twelve to fifteen, sixteen. You're working twelve hours a day. And that's not all mind. Working nights sometimes. You go to work six o'clock in the night, come home six o'clock in the morning. You'd have a 
bit of bread and cheese for breakfast, and your mother would be waiting fo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017 r you to go out to pick blackber}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
ries with her. Yes, you'd come back about twelve o'clock in the day. And then go to bed, and get up to go to work. Well, you see - no, no. And when you
're working days, you rush home, you'd get home about half past six. Well you'd have your tea. And you'd wash. And - you'd sit down and - half doze off and then your mother'd say, aren't you going to Band of Hope tonight? Aye. You'd run down the chapel to
 
Band of Hope. And you'd sit by the - and I've been there thousands of times and I haven't heard nothing they've said. Gone off to sleep while you're in the Band of Hope. See? This is the sort of thing, and then - on a Saturday, you would come home and you
 had this three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
pence or sixpence in your pocket. Eeh, you'd be a millionaire. You'd go out on the road, play football. Marble, anything that was going along, tease anybody, have a bit of fun. Then about seven o'clock at night you'd go and spend this here t
anner. Couple of chips, fish and chips or faggot and peas for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14955578\charrsid13850017  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8662948\charrsid13850017 
ha'ence. Packet of Woodbine, or - packet of Lucky Star, three in a packet for a penny. Box of matches but you had to keep a ha'penny for the collection next - on the Sunday. And - we didn't used to think that we were done well - poor by.
